title: Predictive Model for the [Rh2(esp)2]‑Catalyzed Intermolecular C(sp3)–H Bond Insertion of β‑Carbonyl Ester Carbenes: Interplay between Theory and Experiment

reactions.text: In contrast to the clean reactions of the aryl ketones, the reactions with other carbonyl classes did not give appreciable amounts of Wolff rearrangement products and other degradation pathways are evident. In the case of the alkyl ketones, the observed data again are consistent with the prediction of the model stating that lesser steric effects yield more C–H insertion product. Indeed, while methyl ketone 1g, with r value of 2.89 Å, reacted favorably to form the C–H insertion product 8g in 75% yield, no C–H insertion product was obtained with t-butyl ketone 1j, with r value of 3.25 Å. Instead, cyclobutyl ketone 10j was isolated as the major product resulting from intramolecular C–H insertion into one of the t-butyl methyl C–H bonds.

Dimethyl diazomalonate 1o is the most commonly studied β-carbonyl ester carbene precursor, and its reactivity for intermolecular C–H functionalization has been established in the literature. Consistent with the literature and for our own benchmark data, 1o formed C–H insertion product 8o in 73% yield (Scheme 2).

At first, we explored simple cyclopropanation of styrene with α-diazo-β-amide ester 1xa. Gratifyingly, we found that the 1xa reacts with styrene 11 (2 equiv) in the presence of Rh2(esp)2 catalyst to cleanly furnish cyclopropane 12 in 78% yield as a 3:1 mixture of diastereomers (Scheme 3).

To highlight the future potential of the reaction, we employed a chiral dirhodium catalyst complex in hopes of observing enantioselectivity (Scheme 4). When the C–H insertion reaction described earlier was performed with diazoamide 1xa and cyclohexane in the presence of Rh2(S-PTAD)4 (1 mol %), the C–H alkylation product 8xa was obtained in 26% ee (2:1 er), albeit with a lower yield (25%).

To expand substrate scope, we also studied the reaction of the reactive N-(2-CF3-phenyl) amide 1xf with pentane (13, instead of cyclohexane) in the presence of Rh2(esp)2 catalyst under similar conditions (Scheme 6). Gratifyingly, C(2)–H and C(3)–H insertion products 14 and 15 were formed in 87% yield with 5.8:1 regioselectivity, respectively.
